In this homework, you will use diamonds data set from ggplot2 package. It is automatically loaded when you execute library(ggplot2) so you don’t have to separately load it. Please create a duplicate of diamonds and use that for homework. This will avoid corrupting the original data set.

d <- diamonds # Create a duplicate copy of diamonds data

Make sure that you understand the variables in the data by checking the help file by executing help(diamonds) in the console. The data has five variables that measure the dimensions.

Instructions

  1. You are expected to recreate each plot exactly as shown in the example document.
  2. The objective of this homework is to help you develop fine grain control over ggplot2. As such, please refrain from exercising artistic freedom!
  3. All the plots use theme_minimal().
theme_set(theme_minimal()) # Set document theme to theme_minimal

Q1 (3 points)

Recreate the graph. The parameter that controls transparency is set at 0.3. You need not get exactly the same colors but they must be discrete and should not follow a color gradient.

p1 <- ggplot(d, aes(carat, price)) +
geom_point(aes(fill = as.character(clarity)),
             color = "black",                            # color of stroke
             shape = 21, 
            alpha = .3) +
scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::dollar_format(prefix = "$")) +
labs(title = "Scatterplot of Diamond Prices",
        x = "Diamond Carats",
        y = "Diamond Price")
print(p1)

Q2 (2 points)

The previous graph looks cluttered. So you decided to use facets instead. Recreate the graph:

p2 <- ggplot(d, aes(carat, price)) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = as.character(clarity)),
             color = "black",                            # color of stroke
             shape = 21,
             size = 1,
            alpha = .3) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::dollar_format(prefix = "$")) +
  labs(title = "Scatterplot of Diamond Prices",
        x = "Diamond Carats",
        y = "Diamond Price") +
  facet_wrap(~ clarity, nrow = 2, ncol = 4) +
  theme(legend.position = "none", aspect.ratio = .8, plot.title = element_text(size = 9), strip.text = element_text(size = 6), axis.title = element_text(size = 8), axis.text = element_text(size = 6))
axis.line = element_line

print(p2)

Q3 (5 points)

Next, you want to know whether the price of diamonds depends on table and depth. Note the line types. Recreate the graphs:

p3.1 <- ggplot(d, aes(table, price)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", linetype = "dashed", col = "red") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 100),  # limits increase or decrease your axis limits (increase left hand area)
                     breaks = c(0, 25, 50, 75, 100)) +
  labs(x = "Table",
       y = "Price")

print(p3.1)

p3.2 <- ggplot(d, aes(depth, price)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", linetype = "dotdash", col = "white") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 80),  # limits increase or decrease your axis limits (increase left hand area)
                     breaks = c(0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80)) +
  labs(x = "Depth",
       y = "Price")

print(p3.2)

Q4 (5 points)

Recreate each of the graphs for data exploration:

p5.1 <- ggplot(d, aes(x*y*z, price)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = cut)) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("#99B898", "#FECEAB", "#FF847C", "#E84A5F", "#2A363B"))

print(p5.1)

p5.2 <- ggplot(d, aes(price)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 75, col = "white") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 17500),  # limits increase or decrease your axis limits (increase left hand area)
                     breaks = c(5000, 10000, 15000)) +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::dollar_format(prefix = "$")) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma_format())

print(p5.2)

p5.3 <- ggplot(d, aes(clarity)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = clarity), col = "red") +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
  


print(p5.3)

p5.4 <- ggplot(d, aes(cut, depth)) +
  geom_violin(color = "blue") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  geom_jitter(color = "red", alpha = .05)
  


print(p5.4)

p5.5 <- ggplot(d, aes(x, price)) +
  geom_smooth(method = NULL, se = FALSE, col = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col = "green") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(0, 3, 6, 9))
  


print(p5.5)
